Polly, who would move the restaurant three times in her career as restauranteur, served cheap spaghetti dinners to starving artists.

Also known as the "Hell Hole," the quite unsavory Golden Swan was frequented by local toughs and hoodlums, as well as Village denizens like playright Eugene O-Neil. Known for its rough clientele, it was nevertheless patronized by individuals such as Dorothy Day, (before she founded the Catholic Worker movement). It was also known as a "back and tan" bar because it catered to the sizeable African American cimmunity living in the neighborhood. The Golden Swan was torn down in 1928. to acommodate the new underground Sixth Avenue IRT subway line.
The Café Brevoort inside the hotel was a popular hangout and meeting spot.
The Samovar was a frequent meeting location of the Provincetown Players

Home of the Provincetown Players, founded by Eugene O'Neill and actor/writer Harry Kemp, the playhouse staged the early plays of O'Neill, Susan Glaspell, and poet Edna St. Vincent Millay, among others. It was one of the first "Off Broadway" theater venues.
Upstairs from Polly Holladay's, the Liberal Club hosted meetings of ….

Still in operation primarily as a concert venue, Webster Hall was the site of Socialist, Anarchist, and union political rallies, parties, and costume balls thrown by and for the artist community in the Village.
column9: "Nicknamed the "Devil's Playhouse" by the socialist magazine The Masses, Webster Hall became particularly known for the wilder and more risque events of the time; Marcel Duchamp, Joseph Stella, Man Ray, Francis Picabia, Charles Demuth, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Langston Hughes, Bob Brown, and many other notables regularly attended events there during this time." ("Webtster Hall, Wikipedia) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webster_Hall#1886%E2%80%931940
